column18:
The Future of Healthcare: Computerisation and Automation in Primary Care and General Practice Services

 

Thank you for taking the time to answer this ~10 minute survey. Once you select your occupation, or occupation that best describes your work, you will be presented with a list of tasks understood to be routinely performed by this occupation. The aim is to understand how meaningful automating each task would be, and how desirable automating a task would be for you. 

 

Important Information for Responding to this Survey

 

Question 1For impact on your workload we ask: If it were possible to automate the shown task, i.e. entirely performed by a computer or a collection of technologies, how would it influence your daily workload?

 

There are five options:

1. I do not perform this task.

2. There would be no change in my workload.

3. There would be little change in my day to day workload, and would not save much time.

4. Automating this task would provide me time to work on other tasks in my workload.

5. Automating this task would eliminate a core aspect of the work identified in my job description.

 

If you select "I do not perform this task." for the above workload question, we will not use your answer for the second desirability question below. You may either leave it blank or also select "I do not perform this task", but any other answeres will not be collected. You must perform the task to rate the desirability.

 

Question 2For level of desirability we ask: If you perform the shown task, how desirable is it to you if the task was fully automated?

 

There are six options:

1. I do not perform this task

2. Very undesirable

3. Undesirable

4. Neutral

5. Desirable

6. Very desirable

 

There will also be an open comment box after each task where you can provide additional information to help us understand better the tasks you perform and desirability of automating those tasks.

 

Participant Compensation

If you provide us with your email, at the close of the survey we will randomly select one participant to recieve a Â£50 Amazon Gift Card. The email will only be used to provide the gift card code should you be selected. If you wish not to provide your email we cannot contact you for the gift card drawing.

 

Project Information

For your benefit, we have included below a full outline of the information you should know about this survey and our research:

 

1. Study title

The Future of Healthcare: Automation and computerisation in general practice services

 

2. Background and aims of the study

Recent advancements in technology allow an increasing number of occupational tasks to be automated. The effect of this phenomenon on healthcare is still unknown, in part because we have very little data about what tasks in healthcare can be automated. We hope to contribute to this knowledge gap by understanding what tasks can be automated today by state-of-the-art-technology. 

 

3. Why have I been invited to take part?

You have been invited because you have been identified as an experienced professional working in primary care. 

 

4. Do I have to take part?

No. You may choose whether to participate or not, and if you choose to take part, you may withdraw yourself and your data from the study without penalty at any time, and without giving a reason, by advising us (the principal researchers) of your decision. If you have any questions or concerns, please do not hesitate to contact us. To remove yourself at any point, or to inquire about the survey, please email us at eric.meyer@oii.ox.ac.uk.

 

5. What will happen in the study?

If you choose to participate in the survey, you will complete a small questionnaire that should take on average 10 to 15 minutes. You have the opportunity to complete a few questions about your experience with each task we have listed for your operational role and your perception on its ability to be automated. On the last page, you have an opportunity to provide additional information, and a ranking of how confident you are in your answers.

 

6. Are there any potential risks in taking part?

We have done our best to remove any risk as we believe this survey is uncontentious. You may abandon the survey at any time. Demographic information is optional, as are the survey questions. 

 

7. What happens to the research data provided?

Your responses are not linked to your identity and all research data is stored securely on encrypted machines using industry-leading security techniques. Only the principal researchers and their assistants have access to this data. As per University of Oxford data regulations, we are required to store this data for a minimum of three years after publication. No sensitive data is collected. You may request and receive a full deletion of your data at any time, but note that we are only able to do so if you provide your email address or the same IP address that you used to respond to the survey.

 

8. Will the research be published?

We intend to publish and share this research in both peer-reviewed and non-reviewed research papers.  Individual responses will not be published â only aggregate data and analysis will be.

 

9. Who has reviewed this project?

All research in the NHS is looked at by an independent group of people, called a Research Ethics Committee, to protect participantsâ interests. This study has been reviewed and given favourable opinion by  North East - Tyne & Wear South Research Ethics Committee.

 

10. What if there is a problem?

The University of Oxford, as Sponsor, has appropriate insurance in place in the unlikely event that you suffer any harm as a direct consequence of your participation in this study. If you wish to complain about any aspect of the way in which you have been approached or treated during the course of this study, you should contact Professor Eric Meyer (0)1865 287218; eric.meyer@oii.ox.ac.uk, or you may contact the University of Oxford Clinical Trials and Research Governance (CTRG) office on (0)1865 572224, or the head of CTRG, email ctrg@admin.ox.ac.uk

 

11. More information

Should you wish to receive feedback or have any questions about your data and this research, please contact us at eric.meyer@oii.ox.ac.uk. - Selected Choice
